INSERT INTO `contexts` VALUES (1,'Findings apply to enterprise settings with mature codebases. Personal projects and \"vibe coding\" would see much larger improvements but are explicitly excluded. Results should not be generalized to solo developers or early-stage startups building from scratch.',2,'organizational',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:00:18'),(2,'The study covers a three-year period encompassing COVID and AI adoption events, using predominantly private repositories â€” a deliberate choice because private repos offer more self-contained productivity measurement.',2,'scope',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:00:18'),(3,'No breakdown by specific AI tool (GitHub Copilot vs. Cursor vs. others) is provided, making it impossible to attribute productivity differences to tool quality or approach.',2,'scope',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:00:18'),(4,'This is a deliberately informal piece â€” \"scattered thoughts\" by the author\'s own description. No claims are backed by rigorous data or formal analysis. Observations about workflow effectiveness are based on personal network observation, not controlled study.',3,'scope',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:00:58'),(5,'The technology is described as too early and evolving too rapidly for confident predictions about career impact or industry restructuring.',3,'historical',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:00:58'),(6,'As of early 2025, the security landscape is described as fundamentally adversarial and asymmetric: defenders must catch every attack while attackers need only find one path through. This is a snapshot of a rapidly evolving field.',4,'historical',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:01:45'),(7,'The source is practitioner-oriented and explicitly non-exhaustive, drawing primarily on Simon Willison and Bruce Schneier as authoritative references. The attack taxonomy is illustrative rather than comprehensive.',4,'scope',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:01:45'),(8,'No quantitative risk data is provided. Claims about relative risk levels are directionally reasonable but not quantified.',4,'scope',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:01:45'),(9,'Patterns were developed and validated across multiple client engagements at QuantumBlack, AI by McKinsey, and are running in production deployments. The source is authored by a QuantumBlack practitioner and prominently references QuantumBlack tooling (ARK), which introduces potential promotional framing.',5,'organizational',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:02:35'),(10,'No quantitative benchmarks are provided. Performance claims are presented as patterns observed across client engagements but are not backed by controlled measurements or published data. This is practitioner experience, not empirical research.',5,'scope',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:02:35'),(11,'The post focuses on greenfield feature development. It does not address how these patterns apply to legacy codebase migration, incident response, or other development scenarios that do not follow a clean requirements-to-implementation flow.',5,'scope',NULL,'2026-03-03 04:02:35'),(12,'The three-axis formalism model (ceremony, risk, complexity) defines the scope within which UML and formal methods remain valuable. For most VC-funded startups building on commodity cloud infrastructure, all three axes score low and formal methods add little value.',6,'scope',NULL,'2026-03-04 04:19:56'),(13,'These claims about software architecture and legacy are grounded in the commercial and institutional software context of the 1970s through 2025 â€” they are most directly applicable to enterprise, government, and mission-critical systems rather than small-scale consumer software.',6,'industry',NULL,'2026-03-04 04:19:56'),(14,'The observation that software migrations recur permanently applies most forcefully to systems that were successful and widely adopted â€” failed systems simply disappear. The permanence of legacy is a consequence of success, not failure.',6,'scope',NULL,'2026-03-04 04:19:56'),(15,'The claim that architects have shifted from structural to economic/systemic decisions reflects the current era of cloud-dominant infrastructure (AWS, Azure, GCP). This may not hold for organizations building on-premises systems or in domains with restricted vendor relationships.',6,'technical',NULL,'2026-03-04 04:19:56'),(16,'Booch\'s career spans 1979 to the present day; his observations about abstraction transitions and architectural evolution are grounded in direct participation in multiple industry epochs. Claims about historical patterns carry high epistemic weight; forward-looking claims about AI\'s role are more speculative.',6,'historical',NULL,'2026-03-04 04:19:56'),(17,'The findings apply specifically to enterprise software organizations â€” the McKinsey survey covers approximately 300 global enterprises. Results may not generalize to small teams, startups, or individual developers operating outside enterprise constraints.',7,'organizational','Critical scope boundary for all McKinsey survey-based claims.','2026-03-04 07:00:14'),(18,'The analysis assumes organizations are already operating agile structures â€” two-pizza teams, two-week sprints, separate role tracks â€” and are now at the AI-adoption inflection point. The structural recommendations describe the transition from an agile baseline, not from waterfall or pre-agile structures.',7,'historical','Baseline assumption for the structural change claims. Organizations at earlier maturity stages may face different challenges.','2026-03-04 07:00:14'),(19,'The talk reflects the state of enterprise AI adoption in approximately 2024â€“2025, when AI-native operating models were emerging but not yet widespread. The measurement frameworks and role models described are presented as leading-edge rather than established industry practice.',7,'historical','Temporal scope boundary. The landscape is evolving rapidly; some claims may date quickly.','2026-03-04 07:00:14');
