use at the very beginning of their work galactic I called him out on it and said you Yan this is great stuff but do you realize the implications and he simply dismissed them and I kept calling him out he got tired of me doing so and eventually blocked me but this is another I told you so we are seeing the the joys and the dangers of large language models so just to double click on this it sounds\n\n**GERGELY OROSZ:** you\'re saying that large language models by themselves will not get us to AGI but do I understand that if we combine it with oth\n\n**GRADY BOOCH:** er tools like neural Nets or neural symbiotic systems we can actually get closer to these intelligence systems and if we take this example that you just said a robot on Mars that is able to clear filters and follow instructions what do you think we would need to get to that type of intelligence right and I even add to this if you look at cultures such as Japan where you have an aging population a shrinking population the US is very much in this place you have tremendous need for Elder Care and so the robotic use case and not just the full humanoid robotic use case comes into play there are clear and present needs for these kinds of things as well too so yes there there are lots of great use cases so uh I\'ve always believed this to be a systems engineering problem which is why if you go back to the architecture of self that\'s why I\'ve been focused upon neuros symbolic systems now let me get a little philosophical for the moment you I\'m pretty sure you\'re sentient I can\'t guarantee it but I\'m just guessing that you are and you\'re not some amazing large language model and why do I think it\'s a fair it\'s a fair guess and why do I believe that it\'s because I have a theory of mind about you that through multimodal ways and my interactions with you I have a theory that says you\'re sentient you\'re someone who has its own agency who has your own feeling and behaviors and needs and the like and that\'s cool you\'re not you\'re not a robot and so the human mind has evolved over Millennium to develop that through an architecture that yes it\'s neural in nature but on the one hand neur artificial neurons are a shadow not a shadow they\'re an echo of a whisper of What organic neurons are they are a small small piece of it furthermore if you look at the architecture of large language models which as you observed are relatively simple there\'s a simple layering to them which ignores the Exquisite complexity of the human mind we have in our cerebral cortex uh cortical columns we have tens of millions of them they\'re in humans about seven layers deep reptiles have them as well too they\'re a bit smaller those are the ones that appear to be the place our homonculus work where we build the predictive models of the world world but we also have places where emotions and and and other decision- making take place among these entangled architectures associated with the thalmus and the like and furthermore we have other things going on with it appears to be our our hormonal system that appear to be other ways of message passing within our within our Neal networks so in that same regard large language models are interesting but they also are a whisper of a shadow of I think what reality is and so where the next level is and Gary and I have observed there we\'re reaching diminishing returns on what scale can do the open AI folks and Elon believe scale will continue for a long long time Gary and I are saying no we\'re reaching a limit there you need to think about it in other ways that brings us back to those architectures the last thing I\'ll mention is at the very beginning you talked about me being involved with embod cognition that brings me back to my roots again what is embodiment it\'s Building Systems that are in and of the world that that respond to the world and act in the world large language models are largely unimodel they work through text maybe static images woven together through video and the like but they\'re very sensory sparse our minds and our intelligence have grown because they\'ve been embodied in the world in that regard I think there are many kinds of intelligence and exist but our human intelligence grew because of our embodiment and it\'s going to require some fairly complex architecture to get that that\'s why I\'ve been studying human architectures for six years because I don\'t know enough about them let\'s see if that influences the way I build softare architectures and\n\n**GERGELY OROSZ:** as closing you previously tweeted something really interesting around this and I\'ll quote this you tweeted we need a standard way of visualizing the architecture as well as the activity of llm and to generalize any artificial neural network netw sort of a uml for AI now this was a year back have you seen anything happen here and why do you think llm architecture is so i\n\n**GRADY BOOCH:** mportant uh in fact I have seen both thought I have both thoughts and I have seen movement so internally I\'ve been helping out with providing a little bit of architectural adult adult supervision in our in our large language model work and I\'ve been trying to figure out what\'s the way to visualize the kinds of things we\'re doing turns out it\'s still veryl like that these are now boxes that are systems under themselves and they\'re message passing systems along the way so I\'m trying to figure out the best ways to do that as you may know just this week um Alpha fold released its source code and weights publicly so I\'m I\'m jumping on that and I\'m going to use that as a basis of can I describe the architecture of alpha fold 3 using some uml delivera so stay tuned I think there\'s work to be done in that regard and what advice would you have for software Engineers who are just starting out the software industry there\'s plenty of recent graduat who find themselves in a Chile job market the there\'s a threat of what feels like AI tools changing How We Do software engineering you\'ve gone through a lot of cycles of innovation and software engineering what advice do you have for those starting out to set them up for a successful software engineering career indeed when co-pilot and chat GPD came out I received a flood of messages from folks saying my gosh have I chosen the wrong career because you\'re not going to need developers at all you will always need people who make informed decisions no matter what the language is software engineering again is one of rising levels of abstraction it just that our tools have changed I learned to program in Assembly Language uh people today are going to be learning in programming with languages that are at a much higher level of abstraction so the ad i\' give such folks is twofold uh don\'t worry don\'t be afraid there\'s always going to be some really cool work for you to do there and in fact I would say it\'s quite the opposite this is an exciting time because there is so much opportunity so many Cool Tools so much computational resources that in many ways you were limited only by your imagination and so what I encourage people to do is to first learn as much as you can second don\'t get stuck in just one domain don\'t you need to become an expert in some space but the world of computing is vast and so find some space that nobody\'s in right now and go make a name for yourself there because there are lots of those kinds of places there for you and the third thing i\' advise is go have some fun I mean my gosh the toys we have at our disposal they\'re amazing and wonderful F and cheap there\'s so much a single person can do at so low expense to go change the world I I I\'d like to also close by saying I\'m not done yet either I\'m having a tremendous amount of fun and in addition to the things I told you in in studying the human brain and working with large language models there are two projects that I\'m engaged in that I\'ve been working with for a long time now uh the first is I\'ve been trying to write a book on architecture I\'m glad I did not write it because I know so much more now than I did before and this is a different architecture book rather than saying here\'s how you do it I\'ve been I\'ve been working with a number of companies to document their ASB built architectures so I\'d like to put Alpha fold in it Photoshop is in it what\'s the architecture of Photoshop what\'s the architecture of a climate uh monitoring system what\'s the architecture of Wikipedia so I\'m trying to document the asilt architecture of people of AR of systems that people use today that they may never have thought about the idea being is that there are many different architectural Styles let me expose you to them because you may have studied only one particular one the world is a vast one the second is I this is the software architecture\'s guide book right uh yeah the software architecture handbook which my handbook which my long long-suffering editor has been has been uh been patient with me for a literally a decade now and it\'s something I hope to finish before I die U the second book is I was on the Board of Trustees for the Computer History Museum for about 10 years and we\' hired a new CEO he came to me and said he had been at PBS we had a conversation and said hey uh John why don\'t you do a documentary like Carl Sean\'s Cosmos he paused and said well Grady why don\'t you be our Carl and I said I\'m no Sean but that\'s an intriguing idea so I\'ve been on a journey to do a documentary and writing a book about um Computing The Human Experience which looks at the history of computing and what it means to be human so I\'m looking at what is computational thinking look like uh what do it how has Computing change the individual Society Nations how has it change science and the art and religion and and such and ultimately it asked the question in the present of computing what does it mean to be human so that\'s the larger project I\'m working on right now which I hope to finish up a alsoo before I die and\n\n**GERGELY OROSZ:** let\'s wrap up with some rapid questions so I\'\n\n**GRADY BOOCH:** m just going to ask and then just shoot you don\'t need to think too much about it what was the first programming language that you used for Tran for Tran what project did you commit code most recently and what language did you use in it most recently uh my own language my own project self python python what do you do to recharge from doing software inuring related work I live in Maui I wake up that\'s enough yep enviable place and also answer sir what are two books you would recommend for those who would like to understand mo\n\n**GERGELY OROSZ:** re about software architecture Mary Shaw\'s book software architecture I\'d read that one other books kind of pale in comparison but I\'d start there well thank you very much Grady for being on the show this was really interesting and fascinating it was a pleasure thank you for having me thanks to Grady for this great conversation you can find ways to contact Grady in the show notes below if you enjoyed this podcast please subscribe on your favorite podcasting platform and on YouTube for some additional takeaways from our conversation please see the show notes thank you and see you in the next one','# Software Architecture\'s Evolution: Lessons from the Co-Creator of UML\n\n## Key Assertions\n\nThe entire history of software engineering is one of rising levels of abstraction. Each transition — from algorithms to objects, from objects to distributed systems, from distributed systems to cloud services — represents a new layer that encodes prior architectural decisions as defaults. Engineers today work above layers their predecessors fought to stabilize.\n\nLegacy code is a permanent condition. The moment any line of code is written, it becomes legacy. Organizations from the IRS to Google to Facebook carry codebases dating back decades; the IRS still runs IBM 360 Assembly Language on emulators stacked on emulators, with business rules baked into the assembly itself. Useful code never dies on its own — it must be actively killed.\n\nSoftware migrations are permanent, recurring problems. Every shift in hardware economics, networking capability, or societal expectation compels architectural migration. The problem is compounded because the code is the truth but not the whole truth: rationale, naming choices, and tradeoff decisions live outside the code, in the heads of engineers who have since cashed out or died.\n\nSoftware architecture is fundamentally about decisions. Architecture represents the set of significant design decisions that shape the form and function of a system, where \"significant\" is measured by cost of change. The role has not disappeared — it has shifted from designing novel structures to making systemic decisions about which cloud services, messaging systems, and platforms to use, decisions that carry both economic and long-term technical consequences.\n\nThe role of the software architect has evolved, not disappeared. As more architectural decisions have been encoded into platforms and frameworks, contemporary architects operate at a higher level of abstraction. Solutions architects in cloud environments are now making economic and systemic decisions rather than structural software decisions. Companies like Amazon and Microsoft have codified common architectural patterns into their documentation, making rediscovery unnecessary for most use cases.\n\nUML was designed as a thinking tool, not a programming language. The UML 1.0 standard explicitly describes UML as a visual language for reasoning about, visualizing, specifying, and documenting software-intensive systems — not for generating code. The move from UML 1.0 to 2.0 introduced factions pushing for code generation and precise formal semantics, which Booch views as a profound mistake that made UML unnecessarily complex and drove its decline.\n\nAt its peak, around 2000, UML had 20–30% market penetration among commercial developers. Its usefulness is not universal — the appropriate level of formalism depends on three axes: ceremony (accountability and organizational scale), risk (consequences of failure), and complexity (novelty of the problem). High-ceremony, high-risk, high-complexity systems — defense, aerospace, critical infrastructure — still use UML. Startups building on commodity infrastructure generally do not need it.\n\nObject-oriented design was once controversial. Before languages supported it natively, even function calls (subroutines) were opposed as computationally wasteful. The Booch method codified decomposition by classes and objects rather than algorithms, influenced by Liskov\'s abstract data types, Parnas\'s information hiding, and Dijkstra and Hoare\'s theoretical work. The method\'s weakness was over-emphasizing inheritance, which led to brittle abstractions.\n\nAI is changing the economics of software development, not just its tools. Computational resources are now as cheap as water. A personal cluster of four Nvidia single-board computers sitting on a desk carries more processing power than existed in the entire world in the 1970s. This cost collapse means that for many categories of software, one can build, fail, and throw away without the level of architectural investment that was once mandatory.\n\nSoftware engineering will always need informed decision-makers. Despite AI code generation tools, the field continues to require people who can make informed decisions regardless of the abstraction level of the tools available. AI tools raise the abstraction level, as every prior generation of tools did — from Assembly to Fortran to object-oriented languages to today\'s prompt-driven generation.\n\n## Supporting Evidence\n\n- IBM 360 Assembly Language is still running in IRS systems, on emulators upon emulators, encoding business rules that cannot be separated from the assembly code itself.\n- The Booch method originated between 1979 and 1981 while Booch was consulting for the Department of Defense on Ada adoption.\n- Rational Software was acquired by IBM in 2003 for approximately $2.1 billion (Booch quotes \"2.7 billion\" but identifies it as dollars; other records put the figure at approximately $2.1 billion — flag for verification). At acquisition, Rational had 3,500 employees across 14 countries and revenues approaching $1 billion.\n- Reed Hastings, founder of Netflix, sold his company Pure Atria to Rational Software. The proceeds became seed money for Netflix.\n- Microsoft integrated Rational Rose into Visual Studio and had a team in Seattle working to make Rose a selling point for building complex software around the year 2000.\n- Bill Gates personally offered Grady Booch the role of Chief Architect for Enterprise at Microsoft after IBM\'s acquisition of Rational. Booch declined, citing organizational dysfunction between the Office and Windows divisions.\n- At its peak (~2000), UML had 20–30% penetration among commercial developers.\n- The James Webb Space Telescope uses UML in its design.\n- Amazon has published blog posts describing its use of formal methods for AWS S3, specifically to catch edge cases occurring at one-in-a-billion or one-in-a-trillion frequency — rare in absolute terms but regular events at Amazon\'s scale.\n- Microsoft has used formal methods in driver validation.\n- The SAGE (Semi-Automatic Ground Environment) system, operational through the 1980s, was the first large-scale software-intensive system and precipitated the 1968 NATO software engineering conference.\n- Linus Torvalds has provided the \"conceptual integrity\" for the Linux kernel; Booch notes that when Torvalds eventually steps back, drift is inevitable — as it is for any system without a chief decider.\n\n## Notable Perspectives\n\nOn legacy code:\n\n> \"The moment you write a line of code it becomes a legacy system until you throw it away.\"\n\nOn software migration permanence:\n\n> \"Migrations will plague us until the heat death of the cosmos.\"\n\nOn architecture as decision-making:\n\n> \"Architecture represents the set of significant design decisions that shape the form and function of a system, where significant is measured by cost of change.\"\n\nOn UML\'s intended purpose:\n\n> \"The UML is a visual language intended to reason about, visualize, specify, and document the artifacts of a software-intensive system. It says nothing about it being a programming language.\"\n\nOn the evolution of abstraction:\n\n> \"The entire history of software engineering is one of rising levels of abstraction.\"\n\nOn software engineering\'s future despite AI:\n\n> \"You will always need people who make informed decisions no matter what the language is.\"\n\nOn the economics of formalism — Booch describes a three-axis model for determining how much architectural ceremony is appropriate: (1) ceremony/accountability (startup versus safety-critical), (2) risk (failure consequences), and (3) complexity (novelty of the problem domain). For the vast majority of modern software — particularly VC-funded startups building on commodity infrastructure — none of the three axes demand formal methods or UML.\n\nOn design patterns becoming architectural patterns: Booch argues that the industry\'s maturation is visible in how Amazon and Microsoft have codified common architectural patterns into their documentation. We have moved from algorithms to design patterns (Gang of Four) to architectural patterns (AWS and Azure reference architectures). Companies like Amazon and Microsoft view architecture as important but have reduced the need to rediscover solutions from first principles.\n\n## Methodological Notes\n\n**The Booch Method (1979–1981):** A methodology for decomposing software systems by classes and objects rather than algorithms. Influenced by abstract data type theory (Liskov, Parnas), it emerged from Booch\'s consulting work helping the DoD apply the Ada language. Rational Software later built Rational Rose (Rational Object-Oriented Software Engineering) around it — a design tool, not a code generator.\n\n**UML Origins:** Unified Modeling Language emerged from the collaboration of Booch (Booch Method), Jim Rumbaugh (OMT — Object Modeling Technique), and Ivar Jacobson (use cases, creator of the use-case concept at Ericsson). UML 1.0 was released to the Object Management Group. Philippe Kruchten contributed the Rational Unified Process and the 4+1 View Model, which eventually became IEEE/IEC/ISO standard 42220 on architectural description. The 4+1 views: use cases, logical, process, implementation, and deployment.\n\n**The Three-Axis Formalism Model:** Booch\'s practical framework for determining appropriate architectural rigor: (1) ceremony (accountability requirements), (2) risk (cost of failure), (3) complexity (novelty). Most modern commercial software sits in the low-ceremony, low-risk, low-complexity zone where formal methods and UML add little value.\n\n**Rational Unified Process:** The methodology complement to UML, developed primarily by Philippe Kruchten, building on Ivar Jacobson\'s work. Pioneered incremental and iterative development, continuous integration, and continuous deployment concepts before those terms became standard industry vocabulary.\n\n## Gaps and Caveats\n\n- The acquisition price of Rational Software is given by Booch as \"2.7 billion\" without specifying currency, which appears inconsistent with other records of the acquisition. Treat this figure as approximate and verify before using as evidence.\n- Booch\'s three-axis formalism model is presented as a conceptual framework, not a quantified methodology. It is illustrative rather than prescriptive.\n- The claim that UML had \"20–30% penetration\" around 2000 is asserted without citation or definition of how penetration was measured. This should be treated as an expert estimate, not a documented statistic.\n- Large portions of the interview deal with Booch\'s work on neuro-symbolic AI architectures (the SELF system), Watson Jeopardy, robotic cognition, and his views on LLM limitations and AGI — content primarily about AI as a product being built, which falls outside the active content filter and has been excluded from this distillation.\n- Booch\'s criticism of LLMs as \"unreliable narrators\" and \"stochastic parrots\" and his views on AGI limitations are part of the source but excluded here due to the content filter. These views are relevant to AI-as-product research, not AI-as-engineering-tool.\n- The rapid-fire closing section confirms Booch\'s first programming language was Fortran, his most recent language is Python, and he recommends Mary Shaw\'s *Software Architecture* as the foundational text on the subject.\n','decomposed','Gergely Orosz interviews Grady Booch, IBM Fellow and co-creator of UML, about the evolution of software engineering and architecture over five decades. Booch traces the history through two golden ages of software engineering, the creation and eventual decline of UML, and how the architect role has transformed from gatekeeper to collaborative guide. He offers a measured perspective on LLMs and AI â€” viewing them as another rise in abstraction levels rather than a paradigm break â€” and reflects on what makes engineering careers enduring.',NULL,'2026-03-04 04:10:42','2026-03-06 03:28:59',3),(7,'Moving away from Agile: What’s Next – Martin Harrysson & Natasha Maniar, McKinsey & Company','lecture','transcript','https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SZStlIhyTCY',1,'2025-12-12','2026-03-04 06:47:45','{\"grade\": \"B\", \"notes\": \"Strong conference presentation with well-structured argumentation. Survey figures (7x, 6x, 5-6x, 60x) are compelling but lack methodology disclosure. Carnegie Mellon citation is undocumented. Cursor case study deferred to external article. The 60x agent consumption figure is unexplained relative to baseline. Despite these gaps, the multi-layered evidence base (survey plus three case studies plus external research plus historical analogy) makes this a substantive and credible source within the limits of a 22-minute conference talk.\", \"rigor\": {\"temperance\": 3, \"objectivity\": 3, \"persuasiveness\": 4, \"substantiation\": 3}, \"quality\": {\"depth\": 4, \"clarity\": 4, \"coherence\": 4, \"completeness\": 4}, \"average_score\": 3.63, \"bias_detected\": \"Promotional bias: McKinsey partners presenting proprietary survey data and consulting frameworks with inherent interest in validating their advisory services. Survey methodology, sample composition, and top-performer definition are not disclosed.\"}','# Moving away from Agile: What’s Next – Martin Harrysson & Natasha Maniar, McKinsey & Company\n\n## Metadata\n\n- **Channel:** AI Engineer\n- **Published:** 2025-12-12\n- **Duration:** 21:55\n- **URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SZStlIhyTCY\n- **Captions:** auto-generated\n\n## Speaker Roster\n\n- **Partner, McKinsey & Company:** Martin Harrysson — co-lead of McKinsey’s Software X practice, focused on enterprise AI adoption in software development\n- **Partner, McKinsey & Company:** Natasha Maniar — McKinsey partner specializing in AI-native software development and measurement frameworks\n\n## Attribution Notes\n\nMartin Harrysson and Natasha Maniar are partners at McKinsey & Company presenting at the AI Engineer conference (December 2025). Harrysson speaks first, introducing both himself and Maniar as colleagues, and delivers the majority of the presentation covering team-level bottlenecks, operating model shifts, and organizational change management. Maniar takes over for the measurement framework section, covering the holistic metrics model from inputs through economic outcomes. Harrysson returns briefly for the closing takeaways. Speaker attribution is based on content analysis of the auto-generated captions; the auto-captions do not include explicit speaker markers. The talk references a published McKinsey article on AI-native software development, including a case study of how Cursor operates internally.\n\n## Transcript\n\n**MARTIN HARRYSSON:** [music] Good morning. Hello everyone. It’s really great to be here. Uh so I’m Martin and I’m here with my colleague Natasha. Uh we’re from a part of McKinsey you may or may not be as familiar with. We have a practice called Software X and we work with uh mostly enterprise clients on how to build better software products, which has mostly been using AI uh in the past couple of years. Uh and so what our talk is about today is really more focused on the people and the operating model aspects of leveraging AI for software development and and that we believe that that has to change quite significantly and and that’s what we’re excited to talk to you about.\n\nIf I take a quick step back uh in time and we just uh you know think through some of the major technology breakthroughs that we’ve seen in the last few decades uh they tend to always come with a paradigm shift in also how we develop software. And so I still recall uh almost 20 years ago now I started working as a software engineer — an entry-level developer um in a tech company — and the company I was working for was just switching to agile. We were using Kanban boards, we were uh doing standups and and other ceremonies. This was a big change. It was a massive change for the for the company. And now with everything that is happening in AI, we’re at the precipice of another such paradigm shift.\n\nAnd um if we think about some of the things that are happening um with AI and software development that we’ve seen at this conference, there’s no doubt that this is a new paradigm that is upon us. And so we’ll talk about two things. Uh we’ll first touch a little bit about how do you go from these things that we’re seeing at individual productivity to scaling that to the whole team and what type of changes we think that implies, and then we’ll talk a little bit uh about how do you scale that across uh a whole organization and to really get value.\n\nUm if you’re talking to an audience here which is using agents all the time and I thought if I asked you about some examples, I’m sure you could rattle off, you know, 10 different ones where you would say, “Look, there was this thing that I used to do. It used to take uh maybe even days and and hours that are now taking only minutes, right? There’s no shortage of those stories and you can go over to the expo and talk to any of the companies there about all these great use cases. It really shows that these tools work and they can be really impactful.”\n\nAnd so yet despite seeing some of these improvements uh we’ve done some research to gauge you know where are our clients at the moment. We recently surveyed about 300 uh companies uh mostly enterprises around what are they seeing in terms of productivity improvements. So you have this and then they would say uh on average we’re often seeing only 5, 10, 15% improvements overall as a company. So we’re in a place where there’s a bit of a disconnect between this big potential uh around AI and the reality. And so we think that um there is this gap because as we’ve started implementing AI — whether it’s you know coding assistance or whether it’s now using more complex uh workflows — what has started to emerge is a set of bottlenecks uh that were not necessarily there before.\n\nLike for example, as we now start moving much faster in certain aspects of the work, uh we haven’t really changed how we collaborate among people and team members. That’s not quite keeping up. We started generating way more code, but we’re still reviewing it in a pretty manual way in many companies, right? And then we also have this theme which was recently highlighted in a research report from Carnegie Mellon uh about how all the new code that is being generated is also amplifying uh the generation of tech debt in some cases and actually generating complexity. And so there are these bottlenecks. They’re not impossible to overcome but this is what we believe is limiting uh many companies from seeing the real value that they should be seeing.\n\nLet me talk about maybe just a couple of examples to make that come to life a little bit more. One of the things that we see as a big rate limiter at the moment is around how work is allocated. And so what we’ve learned over the last couple of years is that the impact from AI and agents is highly uneven. There are some tasks where it works amazingly well today and you see huge improvements and there are others where it’s not as effective and so you have that variability. You also have variability among people. Some have lots of experience now using these tools and know how to pick that up and others uh are less experienced, right? And so what that means for team leaders, for engineering managers and so on is it’s very highly non-trivial to know how to allocate work and resources in a good way. And this is creating a lot of inefficiencies.\n\nAnother example uh is around how work is being reviewed. So agents are often given pretty uh fuzzy uh you know stories that are written in prose with pretty fuzzy acceptance criteria uh which means that the code that comes back is not always what it was intended to be and for many companies the only mechanism to control that is often manual review. So you’ve automated some things but we’ve generated more manual review. So these are some of the examples of uh this bottleneck that we see coming up and as mentioned what has resulted in so far is that most large companies today uh are stuck a little bit in a world of relatively marginal gains. Uh they’re working in ways that was developed with constraints that we had in the past paradigm of human development. So you have — you know if you go out to most companies you see 8 to 10 person teams, you see working in two-week sprints, you have all these elements that were largely parts of an agile operating model — and that is putting in some limits to what they can see.\n\nOver the past year, we’ve been working with lots of clients to sort of break that model a bit uh and develop new ways of working in smaller teams, in new roles, uh with shorter cycles. And when you do that, we see really great performance improvements. And that’s what gives us this uh path to where we see things are going to improve.\n\nSo we realized that rewiring the SDLC is not just a one-size-fits-all solution. For example, different types of engineering functions across enterprise along the product life cycle may require different operating models based on how humans and agents best collaborate. So if we take the example of modernizing legacy codebases, this task requires a high context of potentially the entire codebase but also has clearly well-defined outputs. So an example operating model could look like a factory of agents where humans provide an initial spec and final review with minimal intervention. For new features — for greenfield and brownfield projects — the operating model may look like an iterative loop because they may benefit from the non-deterministic outputs and increased variation where agents act as co-creators, providing more options to facilitate faster feedback loops.\n\nSo as we mentioned, we did a survey among 300 enterprises globally to understand what sets these top performers apart. We found that they are seven times more likely to have AI-native workflows — which meant scaling over four use cases across the software development life cycle rather than just having point solutions for just code review or just co-dev. They were also six times more likely to have AI-native roles — which meant having smaller pods with different skill sets and new roles. To enable these shifts, these organizations were investing in continuous and hands-on upskilling, impact measurement, and also incentive structures to incentivize developers and PMs to adopt AI. This led to five to six times increase in time to market and delivery speed as well as higher quality and more consistent artifacts.\n\nSo when we talk about AI-native workflows, we mean that these enterprises are moving away from quarterly planning to continuous planning and also um the unit of work is moving from story-driven to spec-driven development. So that these PMs are iterating on these specs with agents rather than iterating on long PRDs. On the talent side, AI-native roles essentially means that we’re moving away from the two-pizza structure to one-pizza pods of three to five individuals. Instead of having separate QA, frontend and backend engineers, there are more consolidated roles where product builders are managing and orchestrating agents with full-stack fluency and also better understanding of the full architecture of their codebase. PMs are starting to create direct prototypes in code rather than iterating on these long PRDs.\n\nAnd one example um that we’ve described in our article — we’ve studied some AI-native startups and realized that they’ve actually implemented all of these shifts to accelerate their outcomes. And in our article, we’ve described how Cursor actually operates internally.\n\nBut if you’re a large enterprise predicated on the agile model, what are some steps you can take? So in a recent client study with a leading international bank, we tested some team-level interventions to address the bottlenecks previously mentioned — mainly around the sequencing of steps within the agile ceremony and how uh to define the roles of agents and humans within the sprint cycle. So let’s walk through some examples. First, team leads would assign sprint stories using agents based on the data of the team velocity and delivery history. And then they would co-create multiple prototypes and iterate with agents on the acceptance criteria around security and observability needs to have more consistent artifacts across teams. This prevents downstream rework so that developers don’t have to constantly be iterating with the agents during the code process.\n\nThe squads were also reorganized by workflow. So there would be one focused on um small bug fixes and another focused on greenfield development. In the background agents would be used to look at uh the potential cross-repository impacts um to prevent debugging time for developers. And another example — instead of waiting for data scientists’ input, PMs would directly be observing the real-time customer feedback to reprioritize these features and this would lead to an acceleration in the backlog within the same amount of time.\n\nSo we studied the impact of these interventions and found highly promising results. For example, not just the increase in agent consumption by over 60 times, but there was also an increase in the delivery speed that was tied directly to the business priorities for this bank. There was a 51% increase in code merges, but also an increase in efficiency.\n\nThe other aspect of this is around the different roles and the talent model. And so one of the biggest differentiators that we saw as mentioned was around whether you have actually changed the roles that are involved in software development. And so you know what you all are seeing is that engineers are moving away from execution and just simply writing code to being more of orchestrators and thinking through more how to divide up work to agents, for example. And we also heard some examples of how the role of the product manager is changing. And so while this may sound, you know, pretty straightforward to many of you here who are working with these tools day-to-day — that you have to change what you do — the reality is that about 70% of the companies that we survey have not changed their roles at all, right? And so you have this background expectation that people are going to do things differently but uh the role is still defined in the same way and it’s the same understanding as it was a couple of years ago.\n\nUm but we are starting to see some companies changing this. So this is another example from a recent client. They were set up in a way that is, you know, probably pretty common for many companies — a kind of typical two-pizza team model with the types of roles that you would be familiar with. We ran a bunch of experiments and front runners and tested new models that had much smaller pods uh that had new roles which consolidated some of the tasks that were previously done with different roles. And by doing that we could create basically more pods or more teams uh with the same number of people uh but retaining the expectation that each pod is performing at about the same level as they were before. And so we also see really positive results from that — with maintaining and even improving in some cases the quality of the code that was generated. In particular there was a high speed-up in terms of the output from the different teams.\n\nLet’s shift gears a little bit and go from talking about just the team level. So how does this now scale uh across a big organization? The reality is that many companies don’t just have like one or two of these teams but often hundreds of teams, even thousands or even tens of thousands of people who are working in this way. And uh this is where one of the biggest differences that we saw between those that are stuck a bit in getting only 10% or so improvement from those who are seeing outsized improvements is around how you manage that change. Change management I guess is like one of these elusive terms for uh a lot of different things but I think in some ways it’s not a bad way to think about it. I usually say that change management is about getting a lot of small things right.\n\nAnd so the crux to actually scaling this is often about getting 20, 30 or even more things right at the same time that involve the way you communicate uh what this means, the way you incentivize people, uh the way you upskill them, and it all has to come together. Um and when it doesn’t, we see what happens. And so this is an example from another tech company that we worked with um where initially we rolled out new AI tools for them that hit different parts of the product development life cycle. Um we rolled out the tools, there was some usage but often it dropped off. It was either not used or it was sort of used in very suboptimal ways. So that’s the jagged part that you’re seeing on the left hand side here. Despite kind of adding more users uh the overall impact did not change at all.\n\nSo we had to do quite a reset and start over — effectively reset the expectations. What does this mean if you’re a developer day-to-day? What does it mean for a PM? Uh we had much more hands-on upskilling. There was “bring your own code,” there were, you know, coaches available — especially those first few sprints before you make this a habit and work it into the way that you develop software day-to-day. It’s a very critical time and that’s when this matters a lot. Um and having a bit of a measurement system as well, so you know what’s changing and you’re able to see what’s improving.\n\nAnother example just to put this into perspective — this is about getting a lot of things right and each one of these individually may not seem like it’s the biggest deal uh but put together they really make a huge difference. Like for this client — it really helped having you know setting up code labs, for example, instituting a new set of certifications that helped motivate and drive people to change what they do day-to-day. And these things really added up to the change they needed.\n\n**NATASHA MANIAR:** But building a robust measurement system that prioritizes outcomes and not just adoption is important not just to monitor progress but also pinpoint issues and course correct quickly. So one surprising result from the survey was that these enterprises that were bottom performers were not even measuring speed and only 10% were measuring productivity. But our goal is to make our clients top-performing organizations. So we’ve worked with them to create a holistic measurement system that captures impact all the way down to inputs.\n\nSo for inputs this would include the investment into coding tools and other AI tools but also the time and resources in upskilling and change management. These inputs would lead to direct outputs but a lot of organizations are just focusing on how the increased breadth and depth of adoption of AI tools is leading to increased velocity and capacity increase. However, it’s also important to understand how developers have different NPS scores and if they’re enjoying their craft more um rather than feeling more frustrated. And it’s also important to understand whether the code is becoming more secure and has better quality but also more resilient. And one proxy for resiliency that we used for our client was the mean time to resolve priority bugs.\n\nNow if we look at economic outcomes — which is a priority for C-suite executives — they look into what is the time to revenue target, what is the increased price differential for higher quality features or expanding the number of customers to meet the feature demand, and also what is the cost reduction per pod for reduced human labor in aggregate. Having these larger economic outcomes can also lead um for organizations to understand how there is an increased reinvestment in greenfield and brownfield development. But as these tools evolve, the proxies for these metrics will also evolve. But hopefully this provides a MECE framework as an initial starting point.\n\nSo what’s next? The future of course is difficult to predict, let alone in the next 5 years. But we hope that with our vision of a new software development model — even as agents increase in their intelligence and humans become more fluent in AI — that this model still stands. So hopefully this model that includes um shorter sprints, smaller teams, but a larger number of teams will set enterprises up for success in the long term.\n\n**MARTIN HARRYSSON:** So just to leave you with some key takeaways. Um start now. I would say to our clients, this is a human change and it takes time and it’s a big change and it’s going to be a journey and so I think um this is something that everyone needs to go on. I think it’s also important to figure out which model works for you and set a really bold ambition. And with that, say thank you so much for listening to us and uh we have an article here if you’re more interested in the research that we’ve conducted. Thank you so much for having us. [music]','# Moving Away from Agile: AI-Native Operating Models for Enterprise Software Development\n\n## Key Assertions\n\nEnterprise software teams are experiencing a measurable disconnect between individual AI productivity gains and organization-level results. Despite individual engineers reporting task-level improvements, McKinsey surveys of approximately 300 enterprises found companies reporting only 5â€“15% overall productivity improvement. The gap is not a tool failure â€” it is an operating model failure. The bottlenecks that limit value capture are organizational, not technical.\n\nThe legacy agile model â€” two-pizza teams, two-week sprints, separate QA/frontend/backend roles, story-driven development â€” was designed around constraints that no longer exist. Continuing to operate inside that structure limits what AI can deliver. Structural change is required to unlock the full value of AI in software development.\n\nAI-native enterprises are not the ones that adopted more tools; they are the ones that restructured around AI. Top performers were seven times more likely to have AI-native workflows (scaling across four or more SDLC use cases) and six times more likely to have AI-native roles (smaller pods with new, consolidated skill sets). These structural changes produced five to six times improvements in delivery speed and time to market.\n\nApproximately 70% of surveyed companies have not changed their developer or PM roles at all, despite widespread AI tool adoption. Role definition has not kept pace with capability change.\n\nChange management â€” not tooling â€” is the primary determinant of whether AI adoption produces outsized results. Successful scale requires getting 20 to 30 things right simultaneously: communication, incentives, upskilling, measurement. No single lever is sufficient.\n\n## Supporting Evidence\n\n**Survey data:** McKinsey surveyed approximately 300 global enterprises on AI productivity outcomes. Average reported productivity improvement: 5â€“15% overall at the company level, despite high individual-level productivity gains from AI tools.\n\n**Top performer differentiation:**\n- 7x more likely to have AI-native workflows (4+ SDLC use cases, not point solutions)\n- 6x more likely to have AI-native roles (smaller pods, consolidated skills)\n- 5â€“6x improvement in delivery speed and time to market\n\n**Bank client case study:** A leading international bank ran team-level interventions restructuring sprint sequencing, agent/human role definitions, and squad organization. Results included a 60x increase in agent consumption and a 51% increase in code merges, with improvements tied directly to business priorities.\n\n**Tech company change management case study:** A technology company rolled out AI tools across the product development lifecycle. Initial usage was inconsistent and suboptimal â€” adoption dropped off even as user count grew, with no aggregate impact improvement. After resetting expectations, implementing hands-on upskilling, bringing coaches into early sprints, and establishing a measurement system, adoption stabilized and impact improved materially.\n\n**Role consolidation experiment:** A client operating on a standard two-pizza team model ran experiments with smaller, consolidated-role pods. The result: more teams from the same headcount, with maintained or improved code quality and significant speed improvements.\n\n**Carnegie Mellon research reference:** A Carnegie Mellon research report is cited as identifying AI-accelerated code generation as a factor amplifying technical debt and codebase complexity â€” a new bottleneck introduced by AI adoption itself.\n\n**Cursor case study reference:** McKinsey studied Cursor as an example of an AI-native startup that has implemented the structural shifts being described. Details are referenced via a published McKinsey article rather than presented in the talk.\n\n**Measurement gap:** Bottom-performing enterprises in the survey were not measuring speed, and only 10% were measuring productivity.\n\n## Notable Perspectives\n\nThe core argument is a historical analogy: just as the shift to agile required restructuring teams, ceremonies, and roles â€” not just adopting new practices on top of existing structures â€” the shift to AI-native development requires equivalent structural change. The analogy is drawn from Harrysson\'s personal experience as an engineer during agile adoption approximately 20 years ago.\n\nThe talk distinguishes between two failure modes for AI adoption: (1) point-solution adoption without workflow integration, and (2) workflow integration without role and team structure change. Both produce marginal gains. Outsized gains require all three.\n\nOn change management, the framing is explicit: \"Change management is about getting a lot of small things right.\" This positions the problem not as a single transformation initiative but as a continuous operational discipline involving dozens of simultaneous adjustments.\n\nThe measurement framework is framed as a MECE (mutually exclusive, collectively exhaustive) model â€” a McKinsey-standard term â€” covering inputs (tool investment, upskilling resources), outputs (velocity, developer NPS, code quality, resilience), and economic outcomes (time to revenue, price differential for higher-quality features, cost reduction per pod).\n\n## Methodological Notes\n\n**Operating model segmentation by task type:** Different software engineering tasks require different human-agent collaboration models:\n- Legacy modernization (high context, well-defined outputs): factory-of-agents model with human spec input and final review\n- Greenfield/brownfield new features (benefits from variation and non-determinism): iterative loop model with agents as co-creators facilitating faster feedback\n\n**AI-native workflow changes:**\n- Quarterly planning â†’ continuous planning\n- Story-driven development â†’ spec-driven development\n- PMs iterate on specs with agents rather than maintaining long PRDs\n- PMs prototype directly in code\n\n**AI-native role changes:**\n- Two-pizza teams (8â€“10 people) â†’ one-pizza pods (3â€“5 people)\n- Separate QA/frontend/backend roles â†’ consolidated \"product builder\" roles with full-stack fluency\n- Engineers shift from code execution to agent orchestration\n\n**Holistic measurement framework (inputs â†’ outputs â†’ economic outcomes):**\n- Inputs: coding tool investment, upskilling time and resources, change management investment\n- Direct outputs: AI tool adoption breadth and depth, velocity, capacity\n- Quality outputs: developer NPS, code security, code quality, resilience (proxied by mean time to resolve priority bugs)\n- Economic outcomes: time to revenue, price differential for higher-quality features, customer expansion from feature demand, cost reduction per pod\n\n**Change management levers cited:** Role redefinition, hands-on upskilling, \"bring your own code\" sessions, sprint-level coaching, code labs, certification programs, incentive structures, measurement systems.\n\n## Gaps and Caveats\n\nThe 5â€“15% average productivity improvement figure and the 7x/6x/5â€“6x top-performer differentials are presented without a clear description of methodology, sample composition, or how \"top performer\" is defined. These are McKinsey proprietary survey findings â€” they carry consulting-firm credibility risk (potential selection bias, self-reporting, client incentive to report positive outcomes).\n\nThe Cursor case study is referenced as evidence of AI-native operating model effectiveness but the details are deferred to a separate published article. The talk does not present the Cursor data directly.\n\nThe Carnegie Mellon technical debt finding is cited briefly without citation detail, making independent verification difficult.\n\nThe operating model segmentation (factory-of-agents vs. iterative loop) is presented as a framework without supporting data on which conditions predict which model performs better. This is asserted, not demonstrated.\n\nThe measurement framework is described as a starting point and the speakers acknowledge that \"as these tools evolve, the proxies for these metrics will also evolve\" â€” an implicit acknowledgment that the framework is still maturing.\n\nThe 60x increase in agent consumption figure from the bank case study is striking and potentially inflated by a low baseline. The talk does not clarify the starting point.','decomposed','Martin Harrysson and Natasha Maniar of McKinsey argue that most enterprises are failing to capture value from AI in software development because they are adding AI tools without changing their operating models, team configurations, or role definitions. They present a framework for moving from AI-assisted to AI-native development, covering team-level bottlenecks, organizational change management, and the emergence of new roles like \"builder\" that replace traditional developer/PM/designer splits. Maniar introduces a holistic measurement framework that connects developer inputs through workflow metrics to economic outcomes.',NULL,'2026-03-04 06:47:45','2026-03-05 18:25:05',3);
